```

Now I'm building the logic to extract item base premiums and calculate the policy base by summing them, then applying item-specific modifiers like the cursed surcharge.
```
I could hardcode the specific premiums for cursed versus non-cursed items to pass the current test, but that won't scale when the next test introduces high enchantment requirements. I think the more computed approach makes more sense—I'll stick with calculating modifiers based on item properties rather than just pattern-matching on cursed status.
```

typescript
const processStep = (step: any): unknown => {
  const items: any[] = step.items ?? [];
  if (items.length === 0) return { premium: PROCESSING_FEE };
  const item = items[0];
  const baseValue = item.base ?? 100;
  let premium = baseValue;
  if (item.cursed) premium *= 1.5;
  premium += 10; // first insurance
  premium += 5; // fee
  return { premium };
};
```

This captures the actual rule structure without being overly complex, and it'll handle future variations like enchantment levels more naturally. I'll go with this truly minimal approach for now.

